item.title: About us
item.dc:creator: designernahiyan
item.content:encoded:
[et_pb_section bb_built="1" module_class="about-us-section banner-section-left primary-color2-banner image-stick-bottom" _builder_version="3.21" background_size="contain" template_type="section"][et_pb_row use_custom_width="on" custom_width_px="960px" _builder_version="3.21" module_alignment="center"][et_pb_column type="1_2"][et_pb_image src="http://bitechx.com/fitprotest/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Layer-1.png" _builder_version="3.21" animation_style="slide" animation_direction="left"]

[/et_pb_image][/et_pb_column][et_pb_column type="1_2"][et_pb_text admin_label="Heading & Description" _builder_version="3.21" animation_style="slide" animation_direction="right"]

I'M BRANDON

& I'M YOUR COACH!

After a lifetime of experience in fitness, I made the decision to pursue it professionally back in 2009.

In order to be fully equipped to serve my clients, I invested thousands of dollars and countless hours acquiring the best available certifications and ongoing education.

But I ended up spending years of my life working under the ceiling of a big box gym for $25 an hour because I didn’t understand the value of what I was providing or how to build a fitness business.

What's the solution? Do what Erin did: create a new program structure that allows you to get compensated for all your hours of professional service instead of just the "in-session" hours.

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section]

item.dc:creator: designernahiyan
item.content:encoded:
[et_pb_section bb_built="1" specialty="off" _builder_version="3.21" module_class="primary-color1-background dark-section video-section fullscreen" template_type="section"][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.21" use_custom_width="on" custom_width_px="960px" animation_style="zoom"][et_pb_column type="4_4"][et_pb_text admin_label="Heading" _builder_version="3.21"]

HAS THIS EVER HAPPENED TO YOU?

[/et_pb_text][et_pb_text admin_label="Description" _builder_version="3.21" max_width_last_edited="on|desktop"]

You think you are charging industry standard rates, at around $65/session. But then the gym you rent space from takes $20 or more right off the top. (If you're working at a big box gym, they probably take 60% or more). Now you're down to $45/session. But we all know that to get that $45 you have to work more than an hour. You have to write that client's program, you have to communicate with them outside of sessions. Then they ask if you'll make them an exercise demo video for when they're on vacation, and you don't ask to be compensated extra because you're afraid you'll lose them as a client if you charge them more. So after all your effort, you're really only making about $25/hour for all your professional service. And that's only your gross revenue! What happens after the tax man comes to your door?

[/et_pb_text][et_pb_video _builder_version="3.21" src="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qWy_aOlB45Y" play_icon_color="#19b78d" /][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section]

As a seasoned fitness professional in corporate gyms for many years, I had just made the jump to begin my own personal training business. I was struggling to put things together, like writing a business plan, creating unique programs, effective marketing, generating new leads, and how to scale and grow my businesses. Brandon’s program provided the tools, clarity, and confidence I needed to fine tune my personal training and finally launch my online training business. His coaching helped me master the proper mindset to be an entrepreneur and the uplifting community of others going through the program was incredible. I recommend this program to any fitness professional who wants to bring more value to their clients, increase their income, and create more free time in their life.

MEGAN

item.title: Privacy Policy
item.dc:creator: designernahiyan
item.content:encoded:
Who we are

Our website address is: https://bitechx.com/fitprotest.

What personal data we collect and why we collect it

Comments

When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor’s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.

An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.

Media

If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.

Contact forms

Cookies

If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.

If you have an account and you log in to this site, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.

When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select "Remember Me", your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.

If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.

Embedded content from other websites

Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.

These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.

Analytics

Who we share your data with

How long we retain your data

If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.

For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.

What rights you have over your data

If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.

Where we send your data

Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.

Your contact information

Additional information

How we protect your data

What data breach procedures we have in place

What third parties we receive data from

What automated decision making and/or profiling we do with user data

Industry regulatory disclosure requirements

I'M BRANDON

& I'M YOUR COACH!

After a lifetime of experience in fitness, I made the decision to pursue it professionally back in 2009.

In order to be fully equipped to serve my clients, I invested thousands of dollars and countless hours acquiring the best available certifications and ongoing education.

After launching my own successful fitness coaching business and building a full time clientele, the gym I was renting space from went out of my business, and I realized that I needed to evolve and develop my skill set to become an online coach.

I've compiled all my knowledge and resources from the last 10 years into one program so you don't have to spend years of your life trying to figure all this out.

Now I'm on a mission to coach and mentor fitness and health coaches like you, so you can live a life of impact while earning what you are worth.

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section][et_pb_section fb_built="1" module_class="flip-card-section" _builder_version="3.22.7" background_color="#000000" background_image="https://fitprobizlaunch.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/sales-page-2.jpg" z_index_tablet="500" global_module="2814"][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.22.7" max_width="600px" module_alignment="center" use_custom_width="on" custom_width_px="600px"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.47"][et_pb_text admin_label="Heading" _builder_version="3.22.7" z_index_tablet="500"]

THE 5 PHASES OF BUSINESS BUILDING

All successful fitness entrepreneurs, including online coaches, create predictable results using a few essential tools and processes. The Fit Pro Business Launcher will guide you through the 5 Phases of Business Building so that you never have to worry about where your next client is coming from.

We'll show you the step by step process to creating world class coaching programs.

CASE STUDY: ERIN

Within the first month of the program, Erin (LiveFitPDX - https://livefitpdx.com) had already begun implementing the principles of Fit Pro Business Launcher. Through some simple modifications to her program structure, pricing, and enrollment presentations, she was able to go from $25/hour average to $73/hour, nearly tripling her earning capacity.

So how do you get results like this in such a short period of time? Read below for the breakdown of her process.

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section][et_pb_section bb_built="1" _builder_version="3.22.7" background_color="#000000" background_blend="luminosity" next_background_color="#ffffff" prev_background_color="#ffffff" inner_width_tablet="50px" inner_max_width_tablet="50px" z_index_tablet="500" module_class="dark-section-centered " background_image="https://fitprobizlaunch.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/barbell-building-challenge-1552252-1.jpg"][et_pb_row use_custom_width="on" custom_width_px="600px" module_class="et_pb_fullscreen" _builder_version="3.22.7" module_alignment="center" animation_style="fold" width="80%" max_width="600px"][et_pb_column type="4_4"][et_pb_text admin_label="Heading" _builder_version="3.22.7"]

HAS THIS EVER HAPPENED TO YOU?

[/et_pb_text][et_pb_text admin_label="Description" _builder_version="3.22.7" max_width_last_edited="on|desktop"]

You think you are charging industry standard rates, at around $65/session. But then the gym you rent space from takes $20 or more right off the top. (If you're working at a big box gym, they probably take 60% or more). Now you're down to $45/session. But we all know that to get that $45 you have to work more than an hour. You have to write that client's program, you have to communicate with them outside of sessions. Then they ask if you'll make them an exercise demo video for when they're on vacation, and you don't ask to be compensated extra because you're afraid you'll lose them as a client if you charge them more. So after all your effort, you're really only making about $25/hour for all your professional service. And that's only your gross revenue! What happens after the tax man comes to your door?

SOMETHING'S GOTTA CHANGE!

It doesn't take long to realize that even if you had an endless supply of clients and you were constantly busy, you're gonna cap out around $48,000/year at that rate. And I don't know about you, but I'd much rather make $140,000/year than $48,000.

What's the solution? Do what Erin did: create a new program structure that allows you to get compensated for all your hours of professional service instead of just the "in-session" hours.

Tim Eshelman

Think about it, how much time have you wasted in just the last month alone, engaged in activities that aren’t actively creating new clients for you? And if you can increase your enrollment percentage by 2x, 3x, or even 5x, how much time would you save each month by not wasting your effort on “free sessions” that don’t truly serve your clients and eat up time that you could be using to create new revenue?

When we first started working together, I had knowledge from a multitude of university courses and prior internships, but had no idea how to apply those concepts in the real world. This program is a fantastic resource for all things fitness related, whether it be movement, sales, nutrition, connecting with clients, or marketing. When we began, I was scatter-brained with little to no sense of direction and he helped me formulate a long term vision with clarity and purpose.”

Tim Eshelman

PHASE 4

“When I first met Brandon back in 2013, I was fresh off an Exercise Science degree and very interested in the personal training business. After working with Brandon as a coaching client, I was able to completely transform my mindset and my business. Not only did we add new skills to my toolbelt, like Kettlebell training, but Brandon showed me how to navigate the business side of this industry and to start enrolling new clients with a few simple skills that no one else had taught me.”

JASON REED

And that’s okay, because we’ve got your back!

Think about it, how much time have you wasted in just the last month alone, engaged in activities that aren’t actively creating new clients for you? And if you can increase your enrollment percentage by 2x, 3x, or even 5x, how much time would you save each month by not wasting your effort on “free sessions” that don’t truly serve your clients and eat up time that you could be using to create new revenue?

I'M BRANDON

& I'M YOUR COACH!

After a lifetime of experience in fitness, I made the decision to pursue it professionally back in 2009.

In order to be fully equipped to serve my clients, I invested thousands of dollars and countless hours acquiring the best available certifications and ongoing education.

After launching my own successful fitness coaching business and building a full time clientele, the gym I was renting space from went out of my business, and I realized that I needed to evolve and develop my skill set to become an online coach.

I've compiled all my knowledge and resources from the last 10 years into one program so you don't have to spend years of your life trying to figure all this out.

Now I'm on a mission to coach and mentor fitness and health coaches like you, so you can live a life of impact while earning what you are worth.

I couldn’t have done this without the Fit Pro Business Launcher, and I’m so excited to start a new life for myself running my own business! You’ve got to do the strategy session with Brandon. JASON R

MARIA

Brandon helped me piece my thoughts together and create some structure so I had a clear picture of the steps I needed to take to improve my business. In the first 8 weeks, I was able to create a standardized method for running my business that allowed me to free up more time and allow for growth. Brandon’s program has set me on a much clearer and focused trajectory.”

HAYDEN OLSON

Before this program, I was struggling for years with clarity, messaging, and branding and trying to get it all to make sense. I had taken countless courses and lost thousands of dollars to other coaches who couldn’t help. But Brandon’s program helped me dig deep and brought to surface exactly how I need to create my coaching program to attract the right clients.”

ALESSIA

After the first month in the program I enrolled over $5,000 in new business on top of my existing clients! I’d recommend this to anyone who feels like they are just getting by, or just getting started, but who wants to create predictable outcomes for their business and their life.”

BERLEY WHITE

It has practical, easy-to-access strategies that you can take immediate action on, and the coaching piece helps facilitate that action for those who are ready to create not just a job, but a career in this field. Brandon’s program helped me fine-tune my transformational programming and gave me all the right business tools that I continue to use -- because they work!”

SASHA

I was struggling to put things together, like writing a business plan, creating unique programs, effective marketing, generating new leads, and how to scale and grow my businesses. Brandon’s program provided the tools, clarity, and confidence I needed to fine tune my personal training and finally launch my online training business. His coaching helped me master the proper mindset to be an entrepreneur and the uplifting community of others going through the program was incredible. I recommend this program to any fitness professional who wants to bring more value to their clients, increase their income, and create more free time in their life."

MEGAN

Through his program, I was finally able to connect the dots and create systems that I could use with any client. This program is a fantastic resource for all things fitness related, whether it be movement, sales, nutrition, connecting with clients, or marketing. When we began, I was scatter-brained with little to no sense of direction and he helped me formulate a long term vision with clarity and purpose.”

Tim Eshelman

Within those first few months, I was able to really gain confidence in my path, and many amazing new opportunities flourished because I was able to welcome them into my life as I got more structured. ​​​​​​​​​I recommend Brandon’s program to anyone (especially entrepreneurs) who lack a little direction/focus and want to level up their business.”

HAS THIS EVER HAPPENED TO YOU?

[/et_pb_text][et_pb_text admin_label="Description" _builder_version="3.21" max_width_last_edited="on|desktop"]

You think you are charging industry standard rates, at around $65/session. But then the gym you rent space from takes $20 or more right off the top. (If you're working at a big box gym, they probably take 60% or more). Now you're down to $45/session. But we all know that to get that $45 you have to work more than an hour. You have to write that client's program, you have to communicate with them outside of sessions. Then they ask if you'll make them an exercise demo video for when they're on vacation, and you don't ask to be compensated extra because you're afraid you'll lose them as a client if you charge them more. So after all your effort, you're really only making about $25/hour for all your professional service. And that's only your gross revenue! What happens after the tax man comes to your door?

item.title: Sample Page
item.dc:creator: designernahiyan
item.content:encoded:
This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:

Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like piña coladas. (And gettin' caught in the rain.)

...or something like this:

The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.

As a new WordPress user, you should go to your dashboard to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!

item.title: Privacy Policy
item.dc:creator: designernahiyan
item.content:encoded:
Who we are

Our website address is: https://fitpro.bitechx.com.

What personal data we collect and why we collect it

Comments

When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor’s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.

An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.

Media

If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.

Contact forms

Cookies

If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.

If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.

When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select "Remember Me", your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.

If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.

Embedded content from other websites

Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.

These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.

Analytics

Who we share your data with

How long we retain your data

If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.

For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.

What rights you have over your data

If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.

Where we send your data

Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.

Your contact information

Additional information

How we protect your data

What data breach procedures we have in place

What third parties we receive data from

What automated decision making and/or profiling we do with user data

Industry regulatory disclosure requirements

I'M BRANDON

& I'M YOUR COACH!

After a lifetime of experience in fitness, I made the decision to pursue it professionally back in 2009.

In order to be fully equipped to serve my clients, I invested thousands of dollars and countless hours acquiring the best available certifications and ongoing education.

But I ended up spending years of my life working under the ceiling of a big box gym for $25 an hour because I didn’t understand the value of what I was providing or how to build a fitness business.

What's the solution? Do what Erin did: create a new program structure that allows you to get compensated for all your hours of professional service instead of just the "in-session" hours.

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section][et_pb_section bb_built="1" specialty="off" prev_background_color="#000000" next_background_color="#000000" _builder_version="3.21" module_class="video-section " inner_width="auto" inner_max_width="none"][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.21" use_custom_width="on" custom_width_px="960px" module_class="video-row" width="80%" max_width="960px"][et_pb_column type="4_4"][et_pb_video _builder_version="3.21" src="https://vimeo.com/285856421" play_icon_color="#19b78d" animation_style="fade" /][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section][et_pb_section bb_built="1" specialty="off" prev_background_color="#000000" next_background_color="#000000" _builder_version="3.21" module_class="primary-color1-background dark-section video-section fullscreen" inner_width="auto" inner_max_width="none"][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.21" use_custom_width="on" custom_width_px="960px" animation_style="zoom" width="80%" max_width="960px"][et_pb_column type="4_4"][et_pb_text admin_label="Heading" _builder_version="3.21"]

HAS THIS EVER HAPPENED TO YOU?

[/et_pb_text][et_pb_text _builder_version="3.21" max_width_last_edited="on|desktop"]

You think you are charging industry standard rates, at around $65/session. But then the gym you rent space from takes $20 or more right off the top. (If you're working at a big box gym, they probably take 60% or more). Now you're down to $45/session. But we all know that to get that $45 you have to work more than an hour. You have to write that client's program, you have to communicate with them outside of sessions. Then they ask if you'll make them an exercise demo video for when they're on vacation, and you don't ask to be compensated extra because you're afraid you'll lose them as a client if you charge them more. So after all your effort, you're really only making about $25/hour for all your professional service. And that's only your gross revenue! What happens after the tax man comes to your door?

[et_pb_section bb_built="1" module_class="banner-section contain-image banner-section-right primary-color1-banner image-stick-bottom height-down" _builder_version="3.22.7" background_size="contain" inner_width_tablet="50px" inner_max_width_tablet="50px" z_index_tablet="500" next_background_color="#000000"][et_pb_row module_class_1="banner-text-column" module_class_2="banner-image-column" module_class="banner-row" _builder_version="3.22.7" max_width="960px" module_alignment="center" animation_direction="left" use_custom_width="on" custom_width_px="960px"][et_pb_column type="1_2"][et_pb_text admin_label="Heading & Text" _builder_version="3.22.7" animation_style="slide" animation_direction="left" z_index_tablet="500"]

SOMETHING'S GOTTA CHANGE!

It doesn't take long to realize that even if you had an endless supply of clients and you were constantly busy, you're gonna cap out around $48,000/year at that rate. And I don't know about you, but I'd much rather make $140,000/year than $48,000.

What's the solution? create a new program structure that allows you to get compensated for all your hours of professional service instead of just the "in-session" hours.

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][et_pb_column type="1_2"][et_pb_image src="http://via.placeholder.com/580x576" _builder_version="3.22.7" animation_style="slide" animation_direction="right" z_index_tablet="500" /][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section][et_pb_section bb_built="1" module_class="banner-section contain-image banner-section-left secondary-color1-banner height-down no-padding-top" _builder_version="3.22.7" background_size="contain" inner_width_tablet="50px" inner_max_width_tablet="50px" z_index_tablet="500" prev_background_color="#000000" next_background_color="#000000"][et_pb_row module_class_1="banner-image-column" module_class_2="banner-text-column" module_class="banner-row" _builder_version="3.22.3" max_width="960px" module_alignment="center" use_custom_width="on" custom_width_px="960px"][et_pb_column type="1_2"][et_pb_image src="http://via.placeholder.com/542x640" _builder_version="3.22.7" animation_style="bounce" animation_direction="left" z_index_tablet="500" /][/et_pb_column][et_pb_column type="1_2"][et_pb_text admin_label="Heading & Text" _builder_version="3.22.7" animation_style="bounce" animation_direction="right" z_index_tablet="500"]

"SESSIONS" DON'T SOLVE THE PROBLEM

Her first step was to design a new program that delivered a much higher level of service and support to her ideal clientele.

And guess what happened? Clients started paying her more for better service! Imagine that! Instead of clients always trying to pay you less per session, they are willing to increase their level of commitment and pay you accordingly.

I'm not talking about raising your rates for no reason like so many newbie "coaches" are teaching. I'm talking about a complete professional transformation.

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section][et_pb_section bb_built="1" module_class="dark-section-centered light-section" _builder_version="3.22.7" background_color="#000000" background_image="http://via.placeholder.com/3000x1875" background_blend="luminosity" z_index_tablet="500" prev_background_color="#ffffff" next_background_color="#000000"][et_pb_row module_class="et_pb_fullscreen" _builder_version="3.22.7" max_width="960px" module_alignment="center" use_custom_width="on" custom_width_px="960px"][et_pb_column type="4_4"][et_pb_text admin_label="Heading" _builder_version="3.22.7" z_index_tablet="500"]

SOMETHING'S GOTTA CHANGE!

It doesn't take long to realize that even if you had an endless supply of clients and you were constantly busy, you're gonna cap out around $48,000/year at that rate. And I don't know about you, but I'd much rather make $140,000/year than $48,000.

What's the solution? Do what Erin did: create a new program structure that allows you to get compensated for all your hours of professional service instead of just the "in-session" hours.

item.title: RISE OF THE HYBRID COACH
item.dc:creator: designernahiyan
item.content:encoded:
Why your attempt to take your coaching business online is failing and how to fix it.

Brandon Hofer is a fitness professional with an established track record of success in the industry and a respected background as an independent fitness business owner. He now devotes his time to training others on how to launch a fitness business through his company Fit Pro Business Launcher. He will be sharing his thoughts with you on the challenges of mixing offline and online coaching in a new 5-part series appearing here bi-weekly for the next three months.

Part I - The New Wave

It’s no secret by now. Running a successful business as an independent fitness or strength coach brings with it the seemingly inescapable decision: Work myself ragged to make ends meet or sacrifice a hefty chunk of income to sleep more than 4 hours a night and actually spend time with friends and family.

But those aren’t your only options.

The new wave of Hybrid Coach realizes that leveraging their in-person coaching business as a launching platform for an online income, and then maintaining a portion of their in-person clientele, creates the best opportunity to build a sustainable coaching business long term. By blending a diversity of income streams along with the option for location-independent freedom, the hybrid coach can now create a life by design, rather than being held hostage by a single physical space.

But how do you make this leap without losing all your money on digital marketing and spending 10 hours a day staring at your computer screen?

The prospect of expanding your business and your income to the online realm seems simple enough. Throw together a nice pre-packaged program, slap it on the internet for $19 and sell thousands of copies. Oh, and it’s completely passive, so sit back and watch the money flow.

But for anyone who has tried this version of online “coaching,” you already know that it never works, unless you’re a celebrity who already has a massive following. But what about the rest of us? What about the highly skilled coaches who have legitimate programs and experience to share with the world? How do we rise above the noise of the online fitness industry, get noticed by those we can truly help, and inspire them to take the step forward to change their lives?

Throughout my years as a business coach to fitness professionals, I have noticed one dominant problem that prevents skilled coaches from expanding their business online. When they don’t understand how to deliver real value digitally, then any attempt to create a business in that space will inevitably fail.

Think about it, when you coach someone in person, the primary value you provide is your physical presence, along with your knowledge and expertise. It gets people through the front door. It motivates them to show up and do the work. But when you can’t be physically present, there has to be a new delivery system, along with the acknowledgment that you’ll serve a different type of client when you venture into the online realm.

Let me explain.

A NEW PROGRAM, A NEW CLIENT TYPE

The first step in this process is creating a new type of program, and making the shift from promoting specific workout styles to becoming an advocate of transformative outcomes.

What does this mean? To be blunt, it means that the new client type that is looking for you online right now doesn’t care about Barbells, Burpees, Diet Plans, Kettlebells, CrossFit, Orange Theory, or the latest debate about the nuanced definition of yoga. We care. But they don’t.

They’re concerned that they can’t get an erection because the extra weight they’re carrying in their belly has drastically influenced their testosterone levels. They’re concerned that their low energy level is affecting work performance and they need that promotion to pay off their debt. They’re concerned that their spouse may not find them attractive anymore after 2 kids and 20 extra pounds. They want the overwhelming feeling of accomplishment and heightened social status when they finish that obstacle race.

When you can speak directly to someone’s pain in an empathetic way and also give them hope that you can guide them through the wilderness, and when you can show them how to reclaim their identity as the hero of their own story, they will be lining up to hire you as their coach.

The new client type that is actively looking for the new wave of Hybrid Coach doesn’t want to show up to one specific physical location and spend an hour with you 3 days per week. They want to remedy the pain that their life situation is causing them, and they want to know that your process takes them to their vision of a better life.

This client type doesn’t need more information, they need direction. They need you to deliver each sequential step in the process and be present in every way except standing next to them while they workout.

And think about it: If you could drastically reduce the number of hours you spend in the gym or at your box, earn more income than you are right now, and continue to deliver the same caliber of results, wouldn’t you want that?

And if you knew exactly how to connect with a new type of client so that you were never dependent only on your in-person clientele to make ends meet, what would stop you from making the shift and evolving your professional presence?

ONLINE VALUE DELIVERY

But the question remains: how do I deliver real value and transformational outcomes via the online channel without falling right back into the session-by-session business model?

Throughout the coming year, I’ll be providing ongoing support and guidance to help you make this transition. But for today, here are the Top 3 Strategic Transitions you have to make if you’d like to join the ranks of the new wave of Hybrid Coach.

1.     CLARIFY YOUR TARGET - When you have the entire pool of humanity to draw leads from, you need absolute clarity on who you are speaking to with your marketing messaging. Otherwise, your voice just gets lost in the noise and no one pays attention.

2.     PROGRAM FOR DEFINED OUTCOMES - Selling an outcome rather than all the cool features of your program is the foundation of online profit, which is your ticket to freedom.

3.     DIGITAL AUTOMATION - Create additional value-added experiences in your programs that can be delivered even when you are not physically present. For example, leveraging a digital training platform to sequentially deliver the next step in your process can be more powerful for your client and more convenient for you. If you end up explaining something in-person to multiple clients every week, it’s time to automate that piece of your program.

Need help implementing any of this? Contact me directly for help taking your fitness coaching business online.

Next Up: Part II - The Shift (look for it on February 8th, 2019)

item.title: RISE OF THE HYBRID COACH II
item.dc:creator: designernahiyan
item.content:encoded:
Why your attempt to take your coaching business online is failing and how to fix it

PART I - QUICK RECAP

“The new client type that is actively looking for the new wave of Hybrid Coach doesn’t want to show up to one specific physical location and spend an hour with you 3 days per week. They want to remedy the pain that their life situation is causing them, and they want to know that your process takes them to their vision of a better life.

This client type doesn’t need more information, they need direction. They need you to deliver each sequential step in the process and be present in every way except standing next to them while they workout.”

THE SHIFT

In order for you to become a Hybrid Coach, a massive shift has to take place, not just in the way you deliver your service to your new clientele, but in the way you envision your role throughout the process.

The shift I’m talking about is letting go of the default delivery system. Over the years, you’ve gotten very good at writing your client’s program, then standing next to them as they implement that program. It’s a very good system. It’s not broken. It’s just not the best way to leverage your time and impact the most people, especially if your aim is to take your business to the online realm so you can boost your earning capacity.

The Hybrid Coach acknowledges that this shift takes place in 3 distinct areas of their business:

1.     A shift in the way you design your programs - The default way of designing a program usually involves writing everything from scratch based on every individual client. But when you start to specialize in solving a certain type of problem for your clients, you’ll begin to notice recurring patterns, and at some point you’ll have to submit to the fact that even though we are all unique, there are common threads that run throughout these “customized” programs.

As you develop mastery around your process, you’ll notice that much of what you teach and coach clients through can be systemized. This is the beginning of automation and freeing up more of your time so you can scale your business. It is also the first phase of breaking free from the session by session mentality, which always results in getting paid per hour rather than per total program.

This is a bold step forward in creating a true business, trusting that your process can be delivered partially without you present.

2.     A shift in the way you deliver your programs - Here’s where things can get tricky, especially for those who are attached to the default method of program delivery, which is always being physically present. But savvy coaches quickly realize that most clients need your support and coaching outside of the gym more than they do inside the gym.

If you’ve been coaching in-person only for awhile, it may be a challenge to believe that there is a different client type out there, one who truly does not want you to be with them while they are working out. It’s the type of client who will pay more for a proven system and structured plan than they would for sessions with you. And when you embrace the reality of this new client type, you’ll also gain new insight into how to deliver your program.

There are countless communication mediums available to us, whether it’s texting, e-mail, Voxer, Marco Polo, phone calls, access to relevant videos, shared folders with program documents, coaches apps, you name it. The point here is not necessarily the specific channel of communication, but that you know how to deliver the right piece of information or support to the right client at the right time. “Just-in-time” coaching very often has a deeper impact than scheduled coaching, though of course both have their place.

Your client might not need you today for motivation to workout at 6am, but maybe they need a quick chat to overcome the temptation to stop for a quick pizza on the way home that night. Which has more impact on their long term outcome?

Your client might not need you to stand there while they get their reps in, but maybe they need a quick message from you reminding them of a technique queue they’ve forgotten. Which one gives a deeper feeling of mastery and progress?

Or maybe they’re just looking for the encouragement and support they need to stop stalling and actually prep their meals this week. Think of the impact of seven consecutive days of rock solid nutrition, week after week, month after month.

The client is paying for the long term outcome, and how that outcome is delivered is irrelevant at the end of the day. What matters is that they get the result they wanted and that their life changes because of it.

3.     A shift in the way you market your programs - This simple shift is from inward focus to outward focus. In other words, when you shift your marketing from “hey, look at me” to “hey, I see you,” your ability to attract your ideal client skyrockets. Everyone is subconsciously asking “what’s in it for me?” as they read the thousands of messages thrown at them each day. And if your marketing messaging doesn’t address at least the surface of that question, no one who isn’t already a fan of yours will pay attention.

Just today I came across a post from a local training studio. It was a picture of a brand new set of clubbells that they had just purchased, letting everyone know about the new equipment. But no one cares. However, they would have cared about a client testimonial praising the relief of shoulder pain that had plagued them for years (which was accomplished with consistent clubbell training). They’re looking for solutions, not methods.

The reality is that when a prospective client feels like you understand their situation or problem, you’ve opened the door for a coaching relationship. And when that client feels understood, and is confident that your process will help them overcome the challenge they face, you won’t need to “close” them on a sale, because they’ll be asking, “when can we start?”

Need help implementing any of this? Contact me directly for help taking your fitness coaching business online

Next Up: Part III - Designing Your Transformational Program

This post is part of a 5-part series appearing here bi-weekly for the next three months and authored by Brandon Hofer. Brandon is a fitness professional with an established track record of success in the industry and a respected background as an independent fitness business owner. He now devotes his time to training others on how to launch a fitness business through his company Fit Pro Business Launcher.

item.title: RISE OF THE HYBRID COACH III
item.dc:creator: designernahiyan
item.content:encoded:
Why your attempt to take your coaching business online is failing and how to fix it.

QUICK RECAP

The new client type doesn’t need more information, they need direction. They need you to deliver each sequential step in the process and be present in every way except standing next to them while they workout.

When you shift your role in the coaching process along with how you deliver your programs, you will attract the new client type and pave the way for a sustainable online business.

PART III - DESIGNING YOUR TRANSFORMATIONAL PROCESS

There is really only one thing standing between you and the income you’d like to be making: your ability to clearly communicate to a prospective client exactly how you can help them transform their life.

That might sound overly simplified, but the longer I coach people, the more evidence I find to confirm it. When I see the trainer with decades of experience still charging people $60/hour, I know it’s only because he hasn’t honed his skill of clearly communicating to people the value that he can provide. When I see an online trainer hawking their programs for less than $100/month, I know it’s because they haven’t figured out how to explain the depth of their coaching process. And here’s the thing: you already have a completely unique set of life experiences, specific skills, and expert level knowledge based on that experience, from which you could design an incredible coaching experience for your clients. But not everyone is aware of their unique expertise, because usually your expertise is something that you are naturally interested in, so it doesn’t seem like anything out of the ordinary to you.

So instead of doing the mentally fatiguing work of self-reflection to uncover the truth of how powerful we are to truly help people through online coaching, we spend years undercharging and struggling to make ends meet while working 80 hours a week. And this is not to pass judgment on you if you’re stuck in that place. I’m just speaking from experience here, and I know how painful it is to wonder why you’re not earning what you know you should be and working a schedule that still allows time for the rest of life.

Jump starting the process of creating a transformational coaching program involves developing 3 distinct areas of your coaching so you can then explain to prospective clients, in no uncertain terms, exactly what you can do for them. This may seem obvious, and if it does, that’s good. The practice of articulating your process shouldn’t be overly complicated. It’s simply a way to get clear on what you’re already doing as a way to prepare yourself to take a portion of your business online, where the sales and enrollment process is quite different than taking someone through a trial workout and connecting with them personally through your physical presence.

1.     Creating a Clear Process

Chances are you already have a process you take people through, but you may or may not have documented this process in such a way that it can be taught to another trainer or clearly explained to a prospective client.

Very often, coaching processes are explained in terms of a linear phasic process. For example, one coach might have assessments and evaluations, followed by a certain set of corrective exercises, then strength training, then adjustments for increased performance. Their process might be described in 4 phases: Evaluation, Adaptation, Growth, Performance. Or any other clever way to describe the process that leads to the big picture outcome.

Another coach might have a more cyclical process that involves healthy movement practices, nutrition coaching, meditation protocols, and mindset coaching for clients who are struggling with not only physical health, but struggle socially and/or emotionally as well. This process might be described as: Movement, Macros, Meditate, Mindset, or any other clever way you can think of to describe how the process works.

The point here is, once you can concisely explain your long term process, you’ve just taken the first step in expanding your business. It’s not a difficult step, it’s just one that most coaches skip, usually because the old way of doing things is more comfortable albeit limiting.

If you can’t clearly describe your process then you’re not ready for a website and digital marketing funnels, because you don’t have an offer yet. But once you can articulate your unique process, you have an offer that can generate revenue through online channels.

2.     Differentiating Yourself

The fitness coaching industry is noisy. But that doesn’t mean you can’t stand out. In fact, the opportunity to stand out is even greater because the industry is flooded with coaches who offer nothing beyond the standard arrangement.

Differentiating yourself begins with identifying your unique life experiences and skills that make you genuinely different than all the other coaches out there. The thing is, you don’t need to connect with every potential client, just the few who will form your tribe. I’m not talking niching down based on demographics or some other useless generic marketing advice. I’m talking about choosing to connect with people based on your unique training process, a new type of client, and a specific desired outcome that you help them achieve.

When you position yourself as something set apart from the norm, you’ll start to attract clients who are looking for something out of the ordinary. One of my clients has created a program that combines structured workouts, intuitive eating coaching, mindset coaching with an emphasis on self-image development, and community support. And the program is delivered in both online and offline formats. As the program develops and evolves she is able to serve more and more people in a truly unique way.

I meet fitness professionals every day who instinctively know that fitness is an amazing tool to help inspire others on their journey through personal growth, but they also acknowledge that there can and must be something in addition to fitness or strength training that can help their client base stay motivated and encouraged.

3.     Method of Delivery

Your method of delivery is the final step in understanding how to clearly explain to clients why your program is different. Coaching and support happens in all kinds of ways, and is certainly not limited to in-person support, though that will always remain one of the most powerful options.

After you are clear on exactly what your process is, and how it’s differentiated in the marketplace, you will naturally begin to discover portions of your process that can be automated, along with the portions that are more appropriate for one-on-one coaching, and those that are best suited for group coaching. When you combine delivery methods, you actually increase the level of impact for your clients, while maximizing your own time spent to deliver their outcomes.

We’ll dig more into this specific topic later in this series, but for now just take a look at how you are delivering the coaching experience and reflect on whether or not your time is being utilized to its maximum potential, and whether or not you are truly delivering the highest impact for your clients.

Once these three key elements are applied to your coaching business, the task of explaining to your clients exactly how their lives can benefit from working with you will become so smooth that the enrollment process will seem effortless compared to before.

For more help and support in making your transition online, join the community here.

Next Up: Part IV - Get the Right Tools and Launch Online

This post is part of a 5-part series appearing here bi-weekly for the next three months and authored by Brandon Hofer. Brandon is a fitness professional with an established track record of success in the industry and a respected background as an independent fitness business owner. He now devotes his time to training others on how to launch a fitness business through his company Fit Pro Business Launcher.
